In the Release Plan, I have prioritized the user stories in the following manner:\\n\\n(1) All high priority user stories are put into either Sprint #1 or #2. In addition, all high priority and high risk user stories are put into Sprint #1. This way, any issues that may cause delay or cancellation can be identified earlier in the project, rather than later.\\n(2) All moderate priority user stories are completed by the end of Sprint #3.\\n(3) Low priority high risk user stories are not put into the first 3 sprints. It is possible that the client may change their mind after seeing the product in action and they may no longer be necessary.\\n\\nIn addition, user stories that other user stories are dependent upon are prioritized over user stories with no dependencies.

In the Release Plan, I have prioritized the user stories in the following manner:\\n\\n(1) All high priority user stories are put into either Sprint #1 or #2. In addition, all high priority and high risk user stories are put into Sprint #1. This way, any issues that may cause delay or cancellation can be identified earlier in the project, rather than later.\\n(2) All moderate priority user stories are completed by the end of Sprint #3.\\n(3) Low priority high risk user stories are not put into the first 3 sprints. It is possible that the client may change their mind after seeing the product in action and they may no longer be necessary.\\n\\nIn addition, user stories that other user stories are dependent upon are prioritized over user stories with no dependencies.
